The potential vegetation was generally defined based on climate variables (
 Köppen, 1936; 
 Holdridge, 1947; 
 Holdridge, 1967; 
 Box, 1981; 
 Box, 1996; 
 Ramankutty & Foley, 1999; 
 Beck et al., 2005; 
 Baker et al., 2010; 
 Ellis et al., 2010; 
 Levavasseur et al., 2012); therefore, the potential vegetation types could be represented by corresponding climate types. Climate types could be objectively classified to different global climate types based on the monthly attributes using the K-means clustering method (
 Mahlstein, Daniel & Solomon, 2013; 
 Zhang & Yan, 2014a; 
 Zhang & Yan, 2014b; 
 Zhang & Yan, 2016; 
 Zhang, Yan & Chen, 2017b). Monthly mean temperature and monthly total precipitation were used as input multivariables that consisted of an 
 n × 24 matrix 
